\pard\f0\fs28  Sect. ANTHEMIS (Ser.{\i  Arvenses} Fedorov). Annual or biennial with much-branched stems. Peduncles sometimes clavate in fruit. Inner involucral bracts with hyaline or sometimes brownish-scarious margin and apex. Receptacle conical or sometimes hemispherical; receptacular scales subpersistent, ending in a short and slightly rigid point. Ligules white, rarely yellow, pink or absent. Achenes with smooth, granulate or rarely tuberculate ribs.
\par

\par

\pard\f0\fs28    {\b 27. A. arvensis} L., {\i Sp. Pl.} 894 (1753). Sparsely hairy to densely pubescent annual or biennial, perhaps sometimes perennating. Stem (4·5-)10-50(-80) cm, usually more or less branched, often from the base, the basal branches as long as or longer than the main stem. Leaves obovate-oblong to obovate, 1- to 3-pinnatipartite or pinnatisect, not glandular-punctate, more or less hairy; lobes acute, mucronate. Involucral bracts hairy, oblong or oblong-obovate, obtuse, with hyaline to brown scarious margin and apex. Receptacular scales acuminate. Achenes turbinate, (9-)10(-11)-ribbed; ribs obtuse, separated by narrow, deep furrows, smooth.{\i  Most of Europe except the extreme north.} All except Az Fa Sb.
\par

